India's New Hope
Cambridge, USA — India's latest election may be the most significant positive economic event since 2014.
Indian voters decisively rejected the Congress Party, which has almost always ruled India since its independence from British rule in 1947.
They may be happy with this decision.
Sonia Gandhi, the widow of former Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi and the Congress Party's leader, has been ruling behind the scenes since 1998, while Singh has merely been a puppet.
Under her leadership, the Congress Party pursued populist agendas, increasing transfers, which led to India's annual economic growth rate dropping below 4% in 2013.
The per capita GDP still hovers around $4,000, less than half of China's.
The newly elected Prime Minister Narendra Modi promised during the campaign to bring rapid employment and income growth across India, just as he did when he served as Chief Minister of Gujarat.
Under Modi's leadership, Gujarat became a business-friendly state, with expanded economic activities and attracted commercial investments from both within and outside India.
A significant feature of the latest election is that Modi's Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) secured an absolute majority in the Lok Sabha, which is arguably an unprecedented achievement in India.
Therefore, Modi does not need to compromise with other national or regional parties to pursue his legislative agenda.
Two key officials will assist Modi in economic planning.
The newly appointed Finance Minister Arun Jaitley has extensive political experience and previously held a ministerial position in the previous BJP government.
Jaitely is also renowned as a strategic thinker who is sympathetic to commercial interests.
Raghuram Rajan will continue to serve as the Governor of the Reserve Bank of India. Rajan is an outstanding economist, and during his tenure as Governor, he expressed a desire to reduce India's high double-digit annual inflation rate and attempted to reform some of the inherent productivity constraints in India's financial sector.
The measures needed to stimulate economic growth will take time to be implemented and produce results.
But if you want to know whether the new government is taking action to achieve faster long-term growth, you should examine whether progress has been made in the following ten policy areas.
Education.
Although India has excellent higher education and technical institutions, only a small portion of people can access the opportunities these institutions provide, as India's primary and secondary education is very backward.
Only 60% of Indian adults have literacy skills at the elementary school level.
Teachers themselves have poor educational backgrounds and lack motivation, with many never appearing at their schools.
Infrastructure.
India needs better roads and ports to efficiently transport products across the country and around the world.
Recent expansions in private airlines and airports indicate that private companies can also play a role in this area.
Fiscal integration.
Large budget deficits absorb national savings, which could have been used to expand commercial investment. Budget deficits lead to an increase in national debt that can only be financed through future taxation.
Privatization.
The manufacturing and other industrial enterprises owned by the Indian government operate inefficiently and often result in the consumption of national savings.
Selling these enterprises directly helps accelerate economic growth.
Eliminate subsidies.
Subsidies for electricity and energy lead to wasteful over-consumption and increased fiscal deficits.
Although these subsidies are politically difficult to eliminate, they should be replaced with cash transfer payments. Currently, India's cash transfer payments are efficient due to an impressive new fingerprint-based cash transfer system.
Agricultural reform.
Under the current system, the government purchases, stores, and distributes agricultural products.
The result is that large quantities of goods are stockpiled in warehouses, while production incentives are misdirected.
Agricultural markets should be privatized.
Property rights and land zoning.
If you have ever visited Mumbai or other large Indian cities, you will see that land-use restrictions caused by zoning limitations have led to inefficient urban land use, restraining development.
Unclear property rights, especially agricultural land rights, have prevented industrialization in rural areas.
Relax restrictions on foreign investment.
Currently, foreign enterprises cannot be the majority shareholders of banks and insurance companies.
Relaxing these restrictions can strengthen the financial sector and play an important role in economic growth.
Tax reform.
India's complex system of central and state sales taxes distorts domestic trade.
The debate over replacing these taxes with a national value-added tax and adopting a fiscal decentralization system has been ongoing for a long time, and it should now enter the implementation phase.
Corruption.
High-level corruption cases undermine economic confidence and hinder officials' decision-making.
India is also deeply affected by petty corruption, with bribery having become a common feature of all business and personal transactions.
The government should severely punish high-level corruption and curb petty corruption through a new cash transfer payment system.
Pushed by strong growth and expectations of increased profits, India's stock market has already risen by 20% this year.
Now, Modi and the BJP need to prove to the world that they can fulfill their campaign promises.
